1️⃣ What is CPU Scheduling
First principle
CPU is finite.
1 CPU core → runs 1 thread at a time
Multiple cores → multiple threads, but still limited

So the OS needs a scheduler.

What is CPU scheduling?
CPU scheduling = how the kernel decides which thread runs next
The kernel:
Keeps a run queue of runnable threads
Picks one
Runs it for a short time slice (milliseconds)
Switches to another

This happens thousands of times per second.

States of a thread
A thread can be in one of these states:

State                           Meaning 
Running                        Currently on CPU 
Runnable                       Ready waiting for CPU
Blocked/Waiting                Waiting for I/O (DB, disk, network)

⚠️ Runnable threads compete for CPU
Why CPU scheduling becomes a problem under load
Under high traffic:
Too many runnable threads
CPU switches constantly
Cache misses increase
Real work slows down

This is called CPU thrashing.

Key SRE insight
CPU is not slow — contention makes it slow

2️⃣ What is a Thread Pool (AND WHY IT EXISTS)
Naive idea (wrong)
Each request → create a new thread

Why this fails:
Each thread needs stack memory
Each thread adds scheduler overhead
Memory + CPU explode


Thread Pool (correct model)
A thread pool is:
A fixed number of worker threads
Reused for requests

Example:
Max threads = 200

Behavior:
First 200 requests → get threads
Request 201 → waits or rejected


Why thread pools save systems
Because they:
✅ Limit concurrency
✅ Limit memory usage
✅ Limit CPU contention
✅ Force backpressure
This prevents cascading failure.

Key SRE insight
Unlimited concurrency = guaranteed outage

